rsion of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Heth was born in 1360, in Stanthorne, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Thomas Heth, was 26 and her mother, Mrs. Thomas Heth, was 22. She married Robert Swane in 1380, in Stanthorne, Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1360–":"1360–Surnud","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","1355–Male":"1355–Surnud","1382–1479":"1382–1479","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","1338–Female":"1338–Surnud","1338":"1338","1479":"1479","1335":"1335","1355":"1355","about 1359":"umbes 1359","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Stanthorne, Cheshire, England":"Stanthorne, Cheshire, England","Stanthorne, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Stanthorne, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stanthorne, Chesire, England":"Stanthorne, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1360–":"1360–Kuollut","1360–Female":"1360–Kuollut","1355–Male":"1355–Kuollut","1382–1479":"1382–1479","1335–Male":"1335–Kuollut","1338–Female":"1338–Kuollut","1338":"1338","1479":"1479","1335":"1335","1355":"1355","about 1359":"noin 1359","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Stanthorne, Cheshire, England":"Stanthorne, Cheshire, England","Stanthorne, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Stanthorne, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdist